<p class="">Is the Secretary of State aware that those who know General Erskine would know full well that he would not countenance proceedings of this kind for a single moment, and for him to know of these happenings is an absolute guarantee that they will be stopped forthwith? Does the right hon. Gentleman realise that the honour of British troops has been impugned by these allegations, that they have obtained world-wide publicity, and therefore, it is <span id="771" class="column-number" data-column-number="771"></span> in the interests of the country and of the Army that they should be investigated at the earliest possible moment? Will he, therefore, carefully consider the setting up of a court of inquiry along the lines mentioned by my hon. Friend the Member for Ashton (Mr. Wyatt) to satisfy world opinion, and thus decide whether these allegations are true or not?</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
